04219nam a22005295i 9780300138054DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001380547 a10.12987/97803001380542doi  a(DE-B1597)484947  a(OCoLC)952732681  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aJA74.5b.K377 2006eb 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a320.01 92221 aKateb, George, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPatriotism and Other Mistakes /cGeorge Kateb. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Is Patriotism a Mistake? -- t2. Notes on Pluralism -- t3. Undermining the Constitution -- t4. A Life of Fear -- t5. On Being Watched and Known -- t6. Aestheticism and Morality: Their Cooperation and Hostility -- t7. The Judgment of Arendt -- t8. Courage as a Virtue -- t9. Technology and Philosophy -- t10. Socratic Integrity -- t11. Wildness and Conscience: Thoreau and Emerson -- t12. Prohibition and Transgression -- t13. Hobbes and the Irrationality of Politics -- t14. Ideology and Storytelling -- t15. Can Cultures Be Judged?: Two Defenses of Cultural Pluralism in Isaiah Berlin's Work -- t16. The Adequacy of the Canon -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGeorge Kateb has been one of the most respected and influential political theorists of the last quarter century. His work stands apart from that of many of his contemporaries and resists easy summary. In these essays Kateb often admonishes himself, in Socratic fashion, to keep political argument as far as possible negative: to be willing to assert what we are not, and what we will not do, and to build modestly from there some account of what we are and what we ought to do.Drawing attention to the non-rational character of many motives that drive people to construct and maintain a political order, he urges greater vigilance in political life and cautions against "mistakes" not usually acknowledged as such. Patriotism is one such mistake, too often resulting in terrible brutality and injustices. He asks us to consider how commitments to ideals of religion, nation, race, ethnicity, manliness, and courage find themselves in the service of immoral ends, and he exhorts us to remember the dignity of the individual.The book is divided into three sections. In the first, Kateb discusses the expansion of state power (including such topics as surveillance) and the justifications for war recently made by American policy makers. The second section offers essays in moral psychology, and the third comprises fresh interpretations of major thinkers in the tradition of political thought, from Socrates to Arendt.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aPolitical ethics. 0aPolitical psychology. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300138054423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300138054.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles